=======================================================================
  1. CORE ARCHITECTURE & SERVLET INTEGRATION
=======================================================================

  Spring Security plugs into the Java Servlet filter chain.
  Every HTTP request passes through Servlet filters BEFORE reaching
  a Spring DispatcherServlet or controller.

  REQUEST ENTRY PATH
  ------------------

  [Browser / Client]
       |
       | HTTP Request
       v
  [Servlet Container (Tomcat / Jetty / Undertow)]
       |
       | Servlet Filter chain
       v
  [DelegatingFilterProxy]
       |   - Registered as a standard Servlet filter
       |   - Bridges Servlet world -> Spring ApplicationContext
       |   - Looks up "springSecurityFilterChain" bean by name
       |   - Delegates all work to that bean
       v
  [FilterChainProxy]  (the "springSecurityFilterChain" bean)
       |   - Holds a list of SecurityFilterChain objects
       |   - Matches request URL against each chain's RequestMatcher
       |   - Picks first matching chain and runs its filters
       |   - Provides a clean dispatch error handling boundary
       v
  [SecurityFilterChain #1]  e.g. matches /api/**
  [SecurityFilterChain #2]  e.g. matches /admin/**
  [SecurityFilterChain #3]  e.g. matches /** (catch-all)
       |
       v
  [DispatcherServlet]
       |
       v
  [Your Controller]


  WHY DelegatingFilterProxy EXISTS
  ---------------------------------
  Servlet filters are created by the container BEFORE Spring's context
  starts. DelegatingFilterProxy is a thin Servlet filter that simply
  holds a reference name ("springSecurityFilterChain") and at first
  use, looks that name up in the fully-started Spring context.
  This is what allows Spring's DI, proxies, and beans to participate
  in the filter chain.


  MULTIPLE SecurityFilterChain BEANS
  ------------------------------------
  You can define multiple chains. Each has a RequestMatcher and an
  @Order. The first chain whose matcher fits the request wins.
  Example use-case: one chain for /api/** (stateless JWT),
  another for /admin/** (session-based form login).

  @Bean
  @Order(1)
  SecurityFilterChain apiChain(HttpSecurity http) { ... }

  @Bean
  @Order(2)
  SecurityFilterChain adminChain(HttpSecurity http) { ... }


=======================================================================
  2. SECURITYFILTERCHAIN — EVERY FILTER EXPLAINED
=======================================================================

  Default filter order (Spring Security 6). Filters run top to bottom.
  You can insert custom filters at any position.

  Position  Filter Name                              Purpose
  --------  ---------------------------------------  ----------------------------
  100       DisableEncodeUrlFilter                   Prevents session ID in URL
  200       WebAsyncManagerIntegrationFilter         Propagates SecurityContext to async threads
  300       SecurityContextHolderFilter              Loads/saves SecurityContext  (replaces old Persistence filter in Security 6)
  400       HeaderWriterFilter                       Adds security headers (X-Frame-Options etc.)
  500       CorsFilter                               Handles CORS preflight
  600       CsrfFilter                               Validates CSRF token
  700       LogoutFilter                             Handles /logout
  800       UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter     Form login
  900       DefaultLoginPageGeneratingFilter         Auto login page
  1000      DefaultLogoutPageGeneratingFilter        Auto logout page
  1100      BasicAuthenticationFilter               HTTP Basic auth header
  1200      RequestCacheAwareFilter                  Replays saved request after login redirect
  1300      SecurityContextHolderAwareFilter         Wraps request with security-aware methods
  1400      AnonymousAuthenticationFilter            Sets anonymous auth if no auth set yet
  1500      SessionManagementFilter                  Session fixation, concurrent sessions
  1600      ExceptionTranslationFilter               Catches AccessDenied andAuthenticationException,translates to HTTP errors
  1700      AuthorizationFilter                      Final access control check


  FOR JWT / OAUTH2 RESOURCE SERVER, these are added automatically:
  ----------------------------------------------------------------
  ~1050     BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter          Extracts JWT from
                                                     Authorization header,
                                                     calls AuthManager


  INSERTING A CUSTOM FILTER
  --------------------------
  http.addFilterBefore(new MyFilter(), UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class);
  http.addFilterAfter(new MyFilter(), BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter.class);
  http.addFilterAt(new MyFilter(), BasicAuthenticationFilter.class);


=======================================================================
  3. AUTHENTICATION ARCHITECTURE
=======================================================================

  CORE INTERFACES
  ---------------

  Authentication
    - Represents who is trying to authenticate (before) or
      who is authenticated (after)
    - Key methods:
        getPrincipal()     --> UserDetails or JWT or custom object
        getCredentials()   --> password (cleared after auth)
        getAuthorities()   --> List<GrantedAuthority> (roles/scopes)
        isAuthenticated()  --> true after successful auth

  GrantedAuthority
    - Single authority string: "ROLE_ADMIN", "SCOPE_read", "read:users"
    - SimpleGrantedAuthority is the standard impl

  AUTHENTICATION FLOW (ABSTRACT)
  --------------------------------

  [Filter extracts credentials from request]
       |
       | creates unauthenticated Authentication object
       | e.g. UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(user, pass)
       |      BearerTokenAuthenticationToken(tokenValue)
       v
  [AuthenticationManager.authenticate(Authentication)]
       |
       v
  [AuthenticationProvider.authenticate(Authentication)]
       |   - checks if it supports this token type
       |   - validates credentials
       |   - returns fully populated Authentication
       |     OR throws AuthenticationException
       v
  [Authenticated Authentication object]
       |   principal   = UserDetails / Jwt / custom
       |   authorities = [ROLE_USER, ROLE_ADMIN]
       |   authenticated = true
       v
  [Stored in SecurityContextHolder]


  AUTHENTICATION OBJECT TYPES
  ----------------------------
  UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken  -- username + password login
  BearerTokenAuthenticationToken       -- JWT bearer token
  RememberMeAuthenticationToken        -- remember-me cookie
  AnonymousAuthenticationToken         -- unauthenticated user
  PreAuthenticatedAuthenticationToken  -- pre-auth (API gateway header)
  JwtAuthenticationToken               -- after JWT validation
  OAuth2AuthenticationToken            -- OAuth2 login


=======================================================================
  4. AUTHENTICATIONMANAGER & AUTHENTICATIONPROVIDER
=======================================================================

  AuthenticationManager
  ----------------------
  Interface with one method:
    Authentication authenticate(Authentication auth)
                                throws AuthenticationException;

  ProviderManager is the standard implementation.
  It holds a list of AuthenticationProviders and tries each one.
  If a provider supports the token type it processes it.
  If no provider succeeds, it throws AuthenticationException.
  It can also have a parent AuthenticationManager as fallback.

  AuthenticationProvider
  -----------------------
  Interface with two methods:
    Authentication authenticate(Authentication auth);
    boolean supports(Class<?> authType);

  The supports() method tells ProviderManager whether this provider
  can handle the given Authentication token type.

  BUILT-IN PROVIDERS
  -------------------
  DaoAuthenticationProvider
    - Supports UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken
    - Uses UserDetailsService to load user
    - Uses PasswordEncoder to verify password
    - Most common for form login / basic auth

  JwtAuthenticationProvider
    - Supports BearerTokenAuthenticationToken
    - Uses JwtDecoder to parse and validate JWT
    - Converts Jwt claims to GrantedAuthority list
    - Auto-configured with oauth2ResourceServer().jwt()

  RememberMeAuthenticationProvider
    - Validates remember-me tokens

  PreAuthenticatedAuthenticationProvider
    - For requests pre-authenticated by a proxy or gateway

  AnonymousAuthenticationProvider
    - Validates AnonymousAuthenticationToken

  WHEN DO YOU NEED AUTHENTICATIONMANAGER AS A BEAN?
  ---------------------------------------------------

  Case 1 — JWT Resource Server only (most microservices):
    You DON'T expose AuthenticationManager as a bean.
    Spring auto-configures JwtAuthenticationProvider internally
    when you call http.oauth2ResourceServer().jwt().
    Your only required config is a JwtDecoder bean.

  Case 2 — Login endpoint (issuing tokens):
    You MUST expose AuthenticationManager as a bean so your
    login controller can call it directly.

    @Bean
    AuthenticationManager authManager(
            AuthenticationConfiguration config) throws Exception {
        return config.getAuthenticationManager();
    }

  Case 3 — Custom authentication (API keys, OTP):
    Write a custom AuthenticationProvider + custom filter.
    Wire the provider into ProviderManager manually.

  WRITING A CUSTOM PROVIDER
  --------------------------
  @Component
  public class ApiKeyAuthProvider implements AuthenticationProvider {

      @Override
      public Authentication authenticate(Authentication auth)
              throws AuthenticationException {
          String key = (String) auth.getCredentials();
          // validate key against DB or cache
          if (!isValid(key)) {
              throw new BadCredentialsException("Invalid API key");
          }
          return new ApiKeyAuthenticationToken(
              loadUserByKey(key),
              key,
              List.of(new SimpleGrantedAuthority("ROLE_API"))
          );
      }

      @Override
      public boolean supports(Class<?> type) {
          return ApiKeyAuthenticationToken.class.isAssignableFrom(type);
      }
  }


=======================================================================
  5. USERDETAILSSERVICE & USERDETAILS
=======================================================================

  UserDetailsService
  -------------------
  Interface with one method:
    UserDetails loadUserByUsername(String username)
               throws UsernameNotFoundException;

  Called by DaoAuthenticationProvider during login.
  Spring does NOT call this for JWT validation — it only calls
  JwtDecoder. UserDetailsService is for the login step only.

  IMPLEMENTATION
  ---------------
  @Service
  public class AppUserDetailsService implements UserDetailsService {

      @Autowired
      private UserRepository userRepo;

      @Override
      public UserDetails loadUserByUsername(String username) {
          User u = userRepo.findByUsername(username)
              .orElseThrow(() ->
                  new UsernameNotFoundException("Not found: " + username));

          return org.springframework.security.core.userdetails.User
              .withUsername(u.getUsername())
              .password(u.getPasswordHash())       // already encoded
              .roles(u.getRoles())                 // adds ROLE_ prefix
              // OR:
              .authorities(u.getAuthorities())     // exact strings
              .accountExpired(!u.isActive())
              .accountLocked(u.isLocked())
              .credentialsExpired(u.isPasswordExpired())
              .disabled(!u.isEnabled())
              .build();
      }
  }

  UserDetails INTERFACE METHODS
  ------------------------------
  getUsername()             -- the login identifier
  getPassword()             -- the encoded password hash
  getAuthorities()          -- roles and permissions
  isAccountNonExpired()     -- account validity period
  isAccountNonLocked()      -- locked flag (too many failures)
  isCredentialsNonExpired() -- password rotation enforcement
  isEnabled()               -- soft-disable flag

  UserDetailsManager (extends UserDetailsService)
  ------------------------------------------------
  Also provides: createUser, updateUser, deleteUser, changePassword,
                 userExists. Useful if Spring manages user CRUD.
  InMemoryUserDetailsManager and JdbcUserDetailsManager are built-in.


=======================================================================
  6. PASSWORD ENCODING
=======================================================================

  NEVER store plain text passwords.
  Spring Security's PasswordEncoder interface:
    String encode(CharSequence rawPassword);
    boolean matches(CharSequence raw, String encodedPassword);
    boolean upgradeEncoding(String encodedPassword);  // optional

  BUILT-IN ENCODERS
  ------------------
  BCryptPasswordEncoder      -- standard, recommended, adaptive cost
  Argon2PasswordEncoder      -- winner of Password Hashing Competition
  SCryptPasswordEncoder      -- memory-hard, good for high-value auth
  PBKDF2PasswordEncoder      -- FIPS-compliant environments
  NoOpPasswordEncoder        -- TESTING ONLY, stores plain text

  DelegatingPasswordEncoder  -- handles multiple encoders simultaneously
                               Uses {id} prefix: {bcrypt}$2a$10$...
                               Allows gradual migration between algorithms

  RECOMMENDED SETUP
  ------------------
  @Bean
  public PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder() {
      return new BCryptPasswordEncoder(12);  // cost factor 12
      // or for future-proofing:
      // return PasswordEncoderFactories.createDelegatingPasswordEncoder();
  }

  PASSWORD UPGRADE ON LOGIN
  --------------------------
  DaoAuthenticationProvider automatically re-encodes the password
  on login if upgradeEncoding() returns true (e.g. old bcrypt cost
  factor 10 → new cost factor 12). The new hash is saved back.


=======================================================================
  7. SECURITYCONTEXTHOLDER & SECURITYCONTEXT
=======================================================================

  SecurityContextHolder
  ----------------------
  Static class. The central store for the current user's identity.

  Storage strategies (SecurityContextHolderStrategy):
    MODE_THREADLOCAL      -- default. Each thread has its own context.
                             Cleaned up by SecurityContextPersistenceFilter.
    MODE_INHERITABLETHREADLOCAL -- child threads inherit parent's context.
                             Needed for @Async methods.
    MODE_GLOBAL           -- one shared context for the whole JVM.
                             Only for standalone desktop apps.

  Setting mode:
    SecurityContextHolder.setStrategyName(
        SecurityContextHolder.MODE_INHERITABLETHREADLOCAL);

  ACCESSING THE CURRENT USER
  ---------------------------

  // Option 1: Static access anywhere in code
  Authentication auth =
      SecurityContextHolder.getContext().getAuthentication();
  String username = auth.getName();
  Collection<? extends GrantedAuthority> roles = auth.getAuthorities();

  // Option 2: Inject in controller (cleaner)
  @GetMapping("/me")
  public UserDto me(Authentication auth) {
      return userService.getByUsername(auth.getName());
  }

  // Option 3: Direct principal injection
  @GetMapping("/me")
  public UserDto me(@AuthenticationPrincipal UserDetails user) {
      return userService.getByUsername(user.getUsername());
  }

  // Option 4: JWT claims directly
  @GetMapping("/me")
  public UserDto me(@AuthenticationPrincipal Jwt jwt) {
      String subject  = jwt.getSubject();
      List<String> roles = jwt.getClaimAsStringList("roles");
      return userService.getBySubject(subject);
  }

  SecurityContext PROPAGATION TO ASYNC THREADS
  ---------------------------------------------
  By default @Async threads do NOT inherit SecurityContext.
  Fix options:

  Option A: MODE_INHERITABLETHREADLOCAL (simple but global)

  Option B: DelegatingSecurityContextExecutor (per-executor)
  @Bean
  public Executor taskExecutor() {
      ThreadPoolTaskExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolTaskExecutor();
      executor.initialize();
      return new DelegatingSecurityContextExecutor(executor);
  }

  Option C: SecurityContextHolder.getContext() snapshot + restore
  manually in the thread body.


=======================================================================
  8. JWT — STRUCTURE, GENERATION, VALIDATION
=======================================================================

  JWT STRUCTURE
  -------------
  A JWT is three Base64URL-encoded parts separated by dots:

  eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6Im15LWtleS1pZCJ9    <-- Header
  .
  eyJzdWIiOiJhbGljZSIsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXV0aC5leGFtcGxlLmNvbSIsImV4cCI6MTcxMDAwMzYwMH0
                                                    <-- Payload
  .
  [signature bytes]                                 <-- Signature

  HEADER CLAIMS
  --------------
  alg   -- signing algorithm: RS256, ES256, HS256
  kid   -- key ID (matches entry in JWKS endpoint)
  typ   -- "JWT"

  PAYLOAD CLAIMS (Registered)
  ----------------------------
  sub   -- subject (user ID or username)
  iss   -- issuer URI (must match resource server config)
  aud   -- audience (intended recipient service)
  iat   -- issued at (Unix timestamp)
  exp   -- expiry (Unix timestamp)
  nbf   -- not before
  jti   -- JWT ID (unique, used for revocation/replay detection)

  PAYLOAD CLAIMS (Custom)
  ------------------------
  roles       -- ["ROLE_USER", "ROLE_ADMIN"]
  scope       -- "read write" (space-separated OAuth2 scopes)
  email       -- user email
  tenant_id   -- for multi-tenant apps
  user_id     -- internal DB ID

  SIGNING ALGORITHMS
  -------------------
  HS256  -- HMAC-SHA256, symmetric shared secret
             Both sides need the same key (less secure for microservices)
  RS256  -- RSA-SHA256, asymmetric
             Sign with private key, verify with public key
             RECOMMENDED for microservices
  ES256  -- ECDSA-SHA256, asymmetric, smaller keys than RSA
             Best performance, growing adoption
  RS512  -- RS256 with SHA-512, stronger but slower
  PS256  -- RSA-PSS, more secure variant of RS256

  JWT GENERATION (Auth Service)
  ------------------------------
  @Service
  public class JwtTokenService {

      @Value("${app.jwt.expiry-minutes:60}")
      private long expiryMinutes;

      private final RSAPrivateKey privateKey;
      private final RSAPublicKey  publicKey;

      public String generateToken(Authentication auth) {
          Instant now     = Instant.now();
          Instant expires = now.plusSeconds(expiryMinutes * 60);

          List<String> roles = auth.getAuthorities().stream()
              .map(GrantedAuthority::getAuthority)
              .toList();

          JwsHeader  header  = JwsHeader.with(SignatureAlgorithm.RS256)
                                        .keyId("my-key-id")
                                        .build();
          JwtClaimsSet claims = JwtClaimsSet.builder()
              .issuer("https://auth.myapp.com")
              .subject(auth.getName())
              .issuedAt(now)
              .expiresAt(expires)
              .claim("roles", roles)
              .claim("jti", UUID.randomUUID().toString())
              .build();

          return jwtEncoder.encode(JwtEncoderParameters.from(header, claims))
                           .getTokenValue();
      }
  }

  JWT VALIDATION (Resource Server)
  ----------------------------------
  @Bean
  public JwtDecoder jwtDecoder() {
      NimbusJwtDecoder decoder =
          NimbusJwtDecoder.withPublicKey(rsaPublicKey()).build();

      // Add custom validators
      OAuth2TokenValidator<Jwt> expiry   = new JwtTimestampValidator();
      OAuth2TokenValidator<Jwt> issuer   =
          new JwtIssuerValidator("https://auth.myapp.com");
      OAuth2TokenValidator<Jwt> audience =
          new JwtClaimValidator<List<String>>(
              JwtClaimNames.AUD,
              aud -> aud != null && aud.contains("order-service"));

      OAuth2TokenValidator<Jwt> all =
          new DelegatingOAuth2TokenValidator<>(expiry, issuer, audience);

      decoder.setJwtValidator(all);
      return decoder;
  }

  REFRESH TOKEN PATTERN
  ----------------------
  Access token  -- short-lived (15-60 min), sent with every request
  Refresh token -- long-lived (days/weeks), used only to get new access token
                   stored as HttpOnly cookie or secure storage
                   rotated on each use (rotation prevents replay)

  Flow:
  1. Login -> get access_token (60 min) + refresh_token (7 days)
  2. API call with access_token
  3. access_token expires -> 401
  4. POST /api/auth/refresh with refresh_token
  5. Server validates refresh_token, issues new access_token
     (and optionally new refresh_token — rotation)
  6. Client retries original request with new access_token

  TOKEN REVOCATION
  -----------------
  JWTs are stateless — you cannot "un-issue" one.
  Strategies:
  A. Short expiry (15 min) -- accept small window of abuse
  B. jti blocklist         -- store revoked jti in Redis, check on validate
  C. Token version field   -- store version in DB per user,
                              token valid only if version matches
  D. Opaque tokens         -- not JWTs; require DB lookup every request


=======================================================================
  9. TOKEN GENERATION WITH SERVER CERTIFICATE (RS256 / mTLS)
=======================================================================

  SERVER KEYSTORE SETUP
  ----------------------

  # Generate RSA key pair in PKCS12 keystore:
  keytool -genkeypair -alias jwt-key -keyalg RSA -keysize 2048
          -keystore keystore.p12 -storetype PKCS12
          -storepass changeit -validity 3650

  # Export public certificate:
  keytool -exportcert -alias jwt-key -keystore keystore.p12
          -storepass changeit -rfc -file jwt-public.crt

  application.properties:
  -----------------------
  app.jwt.keystore-path=classpath:keystore.p12
  app.jwt.keystore-password=changeit
  app.jwt.key-alias=jwt-key

  KEY LOADING FROM KEYSTORE
  --------------------------
  @Configuration
  public class KeyConfig {

      @Bean
      public RSAPrivateKey jwtPrivateKey(
              @Value("${app.jwt.keystore-path}")     Resource path,
              @Value("${app.jwt.keystore-password}") String password,
              @Value("${app.jwt.key-alias}")         String alias)
              throws Exception {
          KeyStore ks = KeyStore.getInstance("PKCS12");
          ks.load(path.getInputStream(), password.toCharArray());
          return (RSAPrivateKey) ks.getKey(alias, password.toCharArray());
      }

      @Bean
      public RSAPublicKey jwtPublicKey(
              @Value("${app.jwt.keystore-path}")     Resource path,
              @Value("${app.jwt.keystore-password}") String password,
              @Value("${app.jwt.key-alias}")         String alias)
              throws Exception {
          KeyStore ks = KeyStore.getInstance("PKCS12");
          ks.load(path.getInputStream(), password.toCharArray());
          return (RSAPublicKey) ks.getCertificate(alias).getPublicKey();
      }

      @Bean
      public JwtEncoder jwtEncoder(RSAPrivateKey privateKey,
                                   RSAPublicKey  publicKey) {
          RSAKey key = new RSAKey.Builder(publicKey)
              .privateKey(privateKey)
              .keyID("my-key-id")
              .build();
          return new NimbusJwtEncoder(new ImmutableJWKSet<>(new JWKSet(key)));
      }
  }

  JWKS ENDPOINT (publish public key for resource servers)
  --------------------------------------------------------
  @RestController
  public class JwksController {

      @Autowired RSAPublicKey publicKey;

      @GetMapping("/.well-known/jwks.json")
      public Map<String, Object> jwks() {
          RSAKey jwk = new RSAKey.Builder(publicKey)
              .keyUse(KeyUse.SIGNATURE)
              .algorithm(JWSAlgorithm.RS256)
              .keyID("my-key-id")
              .build();
          return new JWKSet(jwk).toJSONObject();
      }
  }

  Resource server config pointing to JWKS:
  -----------------------------------------
  spring.security.oauth2.resourceserver.jwt.jwk-set-uri=
      https://auth.myapp.com/.well-known/jwks.json

  Or with issuer (auto-discovers JWKS via /.well-known/openid-configuration):
  spring.security.oauth2.resourceserver.jwt.issuer-uri=
      https://auth.myapp.com

  mTLS — MUTUAL TLS (CERTIFICATE-BASED CLIENT AUTH)
  ---------------------------------------------------
  Both client and server present certificates during TLS handshake.
  No bearer token needed. The client cert IS the identity.

  Server config:
  server.ssl.enabled=true
  server.ssl.client-auth=need          # need = require, want = optional
  server.ssl.key-store=classpath:server.p12
  server.ssl.key-store-password=changeit
  server.ssl.trust-store=classpath:truststore.p12  # CA certs you trust
  server.ssl.trust-store-password=changeit

  Spring Security config for mTLS:
  http.x509(x509 -> x509
      .subjectPrincipalRegex("CN=(.*?)(?:,|$)")
      .userDetailsService(userDetailsService())
  );

  Use cases for mTLS:
  - Service-to-service auth inside a zero-trust network
  - High-security APIs (banking, healthcare)
  - IoT device authentication


=======================================================================
  10. AUTHORIZATION — URL, METHOD, EXPRESSION-BASED
=======================================================================

  THREE LAYERS OF AUTHORIZATION
  --------------------------------
  Layer 1: URL/HTTP rules in SecurityFilterChain (coarse grained)
  Layer 2: Method security annotations (fine grained)
  Layer 3: Domain object security with ACLs (per-record permissions)

  LAYER 1 — URL RULES
  --------------------
  http.authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
      .requestMatchers("/").permitAll()
      .requestMatchers("/api/auth/**").permitAll()
      .requestMatchers(HttpMethod.GET, "/api/products/**").permitAll()
      .requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
      .requestMatchers("/api/orders/**").hasAnyRole("USER","ADMIN")
      .requestMatchers("/actuator/health").permitAll()
      .requestMatchers("/actuator/**").hasRole("ACTUATOR")
      .anyRequest().authenticated()
  );

  Rules evaluated in order. First match wins.
  Put specific rules before broad ones.

  MATCHERS
  ---------
  requestMatchers(String pattern)             -- Ant-style path
  requestMatchers(HttpMethod, String pattern) -- method + path
  requestMatchers(RequestMatcher)             -- custom matcher
  mvcMatchers()                               -- MVC-aware matching

  ACCESS EXPRESSIONS
  -------------------
  permitAll()               -- everyone including anonymous
  denyAll()                 -- nobody
  authenticated()           -- any logged-in user
  anonymous()               -- only unauthenticated
  hasRole("ADMIN")          -- has ROLE_ADMIN authority
  hasAnyRole("X","Y")       -- has ROLE_X or ROLE_Y
  hasAuthority("read:users")-- exact authority string
  hasAnyAuthority("a","b")  -- exact authority, any of
  access(AuthorizationManager) -- custom logic

  LAYER 2 — METHOD SECURITY
  --------------------------
  Enable with @EnableMethodSecurity on config class.

  @PreAuthorize  -- evaluated BEFORE method runs
  @PostAuthorize -- evaluated AFTER method runs (can inspect return)
  @Secured       -- simple role check, no SpEL
  @RolesAllowed  -- JSR-250 standard, same as @Secured

  Examples:

  // Must have ADMIN role
  @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
  public void deleteUser(Long id) { ... }

  // User can only access their own data (SpEL with method param)
  @PreAuthorize("#userId == authentication.principal.id")
  public User getUser(Long userId) { ... }

  // Check return value — user can only see their own orders
  @PostAuthorize("returnObject.ownerId == authentication.name")
  public Order getOrder(Long orderId) { ... }

  // Filter input collection — only keep items user owns
  @PreFilter("filterObject.ownerId == authentication.name")
  public void processOrders(List<Order> orders) { ... }

  // Filter output collection — strip items user cannot see
  @PostFilter("filterObject.ownerId == authentication.name")
  public List<Order> getAllOrders() { ... }

  SpEL VARIABLES IN METHOD SECURITY
  -----------------------------------
  authentication          -- the current Authentication object
  principal               -- authentication.getPrincipal()
  #paramName              -- method parameter by name
  returnObject            -- return value (@PostAuthorize/@PostFilter)
  filterObject            -- current item in collection filter
  hasRole('X')            -- shorthand for hasAuthority('ROLE_X')
  hasPermission(obj,'read') -- ACL-based permission check

  LAYER 3 — ACL (ACCESS CONTROL LISTS)
  --------------------------------------
  For per-record (domain object) security.
  Stores permissions in acl_* tables in the database.
  Example: User A can read Order #42, but not Order #43.

  Requires: spring-security-acl dependency + AclService setup.
  Annotation:
  @PreAuthorize("hasPermission(#order, 'read')")
  public Order viewOrder(Order order) { ... }


=======================================================================
  11. OAUTH2 & RESOURCE SERVER INTEGRATION
=======================================================================

  ROLES IN OAUTH2
  ----------------
  Authorization Server  -- issues tokens (Keycloak, Okta, Auth0,
                           or your own spring-authorization-server)
  Resource Server       -- validates tokens, serves protected resources
                           (your Spring Boot microservices)
  Client                -- requests tokens on behalf of a user
                           (web app, mobile app, another service)

  RESOURCE SERVER CONFIG
  -----------------------
  Minimum config — just add to SecurityFilterChain:

  http.oauth2ResourceServer(oauth2 -> oauth2
      .jwt(jwt -> jwt
          .decoder(jwtDecoder())
          .jwtAuthenticationConverter(jwtAuthConverter())
      )
  );

  JWT AUTHENTICATION CONVERTER
  -----------------------------
  Maps JWT claims to Spring Security authorities.
  Default maps "scope" claim to SCOPE_ authorities.
  Override to use your custom claims:

  @Bean
  public JwtAuthenticationConverter jwtAuthConverter() {
      JwtGrantedAuthoritiesConverter converter =
          new JwtGrantedAuthoritiesConverter();
      converter.setAuthoritiesClaimName("roles");  // your claim name
      converter.setAuthorityPrefix("ROLE_");       // or "" for scopes

      JwtAuthenticationConverter authConverter =
          new JwtAuthenticationConverter();
      authConverter.setJwtGrantedAuthoritiesConverter(converter);
      return authConverter;
  }

  OAUTH2 LOGIN (when your app is the CLIENT)
  ------------------------------------------
  http.oauth2Login(login -> login
      .loginPage("/login")
      .defaultSuccessUrl("/dashboard")
  );

  application.yml:
  spring:
    security:
      oauth2:
        client:
          registration:
            google:
              client-id: YOUR_CLIENT_ID
              client-secret: YOUR_SECRET
              scope: openid, profile, email
          provider:
            google:
              issuer-uri: https://accounts.google.com

  COMMON EXTERNAL PROVIDERS
  --------------------------
  Keycloak:
    issuer-uri: http://keycloak:8080/realms/myrealm

  Okta:
    issuer-uri: https://dev-xxxx.okta.com/oauth2/default

  Auth0:
    issuer-uri: https://yourdomain.auth0.com/

  Azure AD:
    issuer-uri: https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant}/v2.0


=======================================================================
  12. SESSION MANAGEMENT
=======================================================================

  SESSION CREATION POLICIES
  --------------------------
  SessionCreationPolicy.ALWAYS       -- always create session
  SessionCreationPolicy.IF_REQUIRED  -- default; create if needed
  SessionCreationPolicy.NEVER        -- never create; use existing if present
  SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS    -- never create or use sessions
                                        Required for REST APIs with JWT

  STATELESS CONFIG (JWT APIs)
  ----------------------------
  http.sessionManagement(sm ->
      sm.sessionCreationPolicy(SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS));

  CONCURRENT SESSION CONTROL (Web Apps)
  ----------------------------------------
  http.sessionManagement(sm -> sm
      .maximumSessions(1)                  // only 1 session per user
      .maxSessionsPreventsLogin(false)     // false = new login kicks old
                                           // true  = new login rejected
      .expiredUrl("/session-expired")
  );

  Requires HttpSessionEventPublisher bean:
  @Bean
  public HttpSessionEventPublisher sessionEventPublisher() {
      return new HttpSessionEventPublisher();
  }

  SESSION FIXATION PROTECTION
  ----------------------------
  On login, Spring by default migrates the session (new session ID,
  old session attributes copied). Options:
  sm.sessionFixation().migrateSession()    -- default
  sm.sessionFixation().newSession()        -- new session, no attribute copy
  sm.sessionFixation().changeSessionId()   -- reuse session, change ID only
  sm.sessionFixation().none()              -- disable (not recommended)

  REMEMBER ME
  -----------
  http.rememberMe(rm -> rm
      .key("my-app-secret-key")   // signs remember-me cookie
      .tokenValiditySeconds(604800)  // 7 days
      .userDetailsService(userDetailsService())
  );
  Login form must include: <input type="checkbox" name="remember-me">


=======================================================================
  13. CSRF, CORS, HEADERS
=======================================================================

  CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery)
  ----------------------------------
  Spring Security enables CSRF protection by default for stateful apps.
  Disable for stateless REST APIs (JWT carries its own proof of origin):

  http.csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable());

  If you need CSRF for a hybrid app (some pages use sessions):
  http.csrf(csrf -> csrf
      .csrfTokenRepository(CookieCsrfTokenRepository.withHttpOnlyFalse())
      .ignoringRequestMatchers("/api/webhooks/**")
  );

  CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)
  --------------------------------------
  Spring Security CORS must be configured BEFORE authentication filters.
  Best practice: configure via Spring MVC @CrossOrigin or WebMvcConfigurer,
  then tell Spring Security to use that config:

  http.cors(cors -> cors.configurationSource(corsConfigurationSource()));

  @Bean
  CorsConfigurationSource corsConfigurationSource() {
      CorsConfiguration config = new CorsConfiguration();
      config.setAllowedOrigins(List.of("https://my-frontend.com"));
      config.setAllowedMethods(List.of("GET","POST","PUT","DELETE","OPTIONS"));
      config.setAllowedHeaders(List.of("Authorization","Content-Type"));
      config.setAllowCredentials(true);
      config.setMaxAge(3600L);
      UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource source =
          new UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource();
      source.registerCorsConfiguration("/**", config);
      return source;
  }

  SECURITY HEADERS (HeaderWriterFilter)
  ---------------------------------------
  Spring Security adds these by default. Override with:

  http.headers(h -> h
      .frameOptions(f -> f.sameOrigin())          // X-Frame-Options
      .xssProtection(x -> x.enable())             // X-XSS-Protection
      .contentTypeOptions(Customizer.withDefaults())// X-Content-Type-Options
      .httpStrictTransportSecurity(hsts -> hsts   // HSTS
          .includeSubDomains(true)
          .maxAgeInSeconds(31536000))
      .contentSecurityPolicy(csp ->               // CSP
          csp.policyDirectives(
              "default-src 'self'; " +
              "script-src 'self'; " +
              "style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'"))
  );


=======================================================================
  14. EXCEPTION HANDLING
=======================================================================

  TWO TYPES OF SECURITY EXCEPTIONS
  ----------------------------------
  AuthenticationException  -- user not authenticated (no/bad credentials)
                              --> HTTP 401 Unauthorized
  AccessDeniedException    -- user authenticated but lacks permission
                              --> HTTP 403 Forbidden

  ExceptionTranslationFilter handles both:
  - Catches AuthenticationException --> calls AuthenticationEntryPoint
  - Catches AccessDeniedException:
      - If user is anonymous  --> calls AuthenticationEntryPoint
      - If user is logged in  --> calls AccessDeniedHandler

  CUSTOM ENTRY POINT (401 response)
  -----------------------------------
  @Component
  public class CustomAuthEntryPoint implements AuthenticationEntryPoint {
      @Override
      public void commence(HttpServletRequest request,
                           HttpServletResponse response,
                           AuthenticationException ex)
              throws IOException {
          response.setContentType("application/json");
          response.setStatus(HttpServletResponse.SC_UNAUTHORIZED);
          response.getWriter().write(
              "{\"error\":\"Unauthorized\",\"message\":\"" +
              ex.getMessage() + "\"}");
      }
  }

  CUSTOM ACCESS DENIED HANDLER (403 response)
  ---------------------------------------------
  @Component
  public class CustomAccessDeniedHandler implements AccessDeniedHandler {
      @Override
      public void handle(HttpServletRequest request,
                         HttpServletResponse response,
                         AccessDeniedException ex)
              throws IOException {
          response.setContentType("application/json");
          response.setStatus(HttpServletResponse.SC_FORBIDDEN);
          response.getWriter().write(
              "{\"error\":\"Forbidden\",\"message\":\"" +
              ex.getMessage() + "\"}");
      }
  }

  WIRING INTO FILTER CHAIN
  -------------------------
  http.exceptionHandling(ex -> ex
      .authenticationEntryPoint(customAuthEntryPoint)
      .accessDeniedHandler(customAccessDeniedHandler)
  );

  SECURITY EXCEPTION HIERARCHY
  ------------------------------
  AuthenticationException
    |-- BadCredentialsException          wrong password
    |-- UsernameNotFoundException        user not found
    |-- AccountExpiredException          account expired
    |-- LockedException                  account locked
    |-- DisabledException                account disabled
    |-- CredentialsExpiredException      password expired
    |-- InsufficientAuthenticationException  need stronger auth

  AccessDeniedException
    |-- (subclasses vary by context)


=======================================================================
  15. API GATEWAY INTEGRATION (Spring Cloud Gateway)
=======================================================================

  Spring Cloud Gateway is a reactive gateway (WebFlux-based).
  It uses ServerHttpSecurity instead of HttpSecurity.

  PATTERN A — GATEWAY VALIDATES TOKEN, PASSES HEADERS
  -----------------------------------------------------

  [Client]
       | Authorization: Bearer eyJ...
       v
  [API Gateway]
       |   - JwtDecoder validates signature + expiry + issuer
       |   - Extracts claims (user ID, roles)
       |   - Adds internal headers: X-User-Id, X-Roles, X-User-Email
       |   - Strips the Authorization header (optional)
       |   - Rate limiting, circuit breaking
       v
  [Microservices] (no spring-security needed at service level)
       |   - Read X-User-Id header to know who the caller is
       |   - Services MUST only be reachable via gateway (firewall)

  Pros: single validation point, simpler services
  Cons: gateway bypass = no auth, single point of failure

  PATTERN B — GATEWAY ROUTES, EACH SERVICE VALIDATES
  ----------------------------------------------------

  [Client]
       | Authorization: Bearer eyJ...
       v
  [API Gateway]
       |   - Routing, rate limiting, logging only
       |   - TokenRelay filter forwards Authorization header unchanged
       v
  [Each Microservice]
       |   - Has its own SecurityFilterChain
       |   - Validates JWT independently
       |   - Fine-grained @PreAuthorize checks

  Pros: defense in depth, zero-trust, services are independent
  Cons: repeated validation overhead per request

  RECOMMENDED — COMBINE BOTH
  ---------------------------

  [Client]
       v
  [API Gateway]
       |   Coarse auth: token valid? not expired?
       |   Rate limiting, DDoS, CORS, header sanitization
       |   TokenRelay forwards JWT downstream
       v
  [Microservices]
       |   Fine-grained auth per resource
       |   @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN') and #id == principal.userId")
       |   Full JWT validation (defense in depth)

  GATEWAY SECURITY CONFIG (reactive / WebFlux)
  ---------------------------------------------
  @Configuration
  public class GatewaySecurityConfig {

      @Bean
      public SecurityWebFilterChain springSecurityFilterChain(
              ServerHttpSecurity http) {
          http
              .csrf(ServerHttpSecurity.CsrfSpec::disable)
              .authorizeExchange(ex -> ex
                  .pathMatchers("/api/auth/**").permitAll()
                  .pathMatchers("/actuator/health").permitAll()
                  .pathMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasAuthority("SCOPE_admin")
                  .anyExchange().authenticated()
              )
              .oauth2ResourceServer(oauth2 -> oauth2
                  .jwt(Customizer.withDefaults())
              );
          return http.build();
      }
  }

  application.yml — routing with TokenRelay:
  -------------------------------------------
  spring:
    security:
      oauth2:
        resourceserver:
          jwt:
            jwk-set-uri: https://auth.myapp.com/.well-known/jwks.json
    cloud:
      gateway:
        routes:
          - id: order-service
            uri: lb://order-service
            predicates:
              - Path=/api/orders/**
            filters:
              - TokenRelay=           # forwards JWT to downstream
              - RemoveRequestHeader=Cookie
              - name: RequestRateLimiter
                args:
                  redis-rate-limiter.replenishRate: 100
                  redis-rate-limiter.burstCapacity: 200

  ADDING GATEWAY-RESOLVED HEADERS TO DOWNSTREAM
  -----------------------------------------------
  @Component
  public class UserContextFilter implements GlobalFilter {

      @Override
      public Mono<Void> filter(ServerWebExchange exchange,
                               GatewayFilterChain chain) {
          return ReactiveSecurityContextHolder.getContext()
              .map(ctx -> (JwtAuthenticationToken) ctx.getAuthentication())
              .map(auth -> {
                  Jwt jwt = auth.getToken();
                  return exchange.mutate()
                      .request(r -> r
                          .header("X-User-Id",    jwt.getSubject())
                          .header("X-User-Email", jwt.getClaimAsString("email"))
                          .header("X-Roles",      String.join(",",
                              jwt.getClaimAsStringList("roles"))))
                      .build();
              })
              .defaultIfEmpty(exchange)
              .flatMap(chain::filter);
      }
  }


=======================================================================
  16. METHOD SECURITY DEEP DIVE
=======================================================================

  ENABLE METHOD SECURITY
  -----------------------
  @Configuration
  @EnableMethodSecurity(
      prePostEnabled  = true,   // @PreAuthorize, @PostAuthorize (default true)
      securedEnabled  = true,   // @Secured
      jsr250Enabled   = true    // @RolesAllowed, @PermitAll, @DenyAll
  )
  public class MethodSecurityConfig { }

  HOW IT WORKS INTERNALLY
  ------------------------
  @EnableMethodSecurity registers AOP advisors (not interceptors as in
  older versions). When a bean method is called:
  1. AuthorizationManagerBeforeMethodInterceptor runs @PreAuthorize
  2. Method executes
  3. AuthorizationManagerAfterMethodInterceptor runs @PostAuthorize

  If authorization fails at step 1, method never runs.
  If it fails at step 3, method ran but result is blocked.

  SELF-INVOCATION GOTCHA
  -----------------------
  If serviceA.methodA() calls this.methodB() inside the same class,
  and methodB has @PreAuthorize, the annotation is IGNORED.
  The AOP proxy is bypassed by self-calls.

  Fix: inject the bean into itself (Spring allows this for @Service):
  @Autowired private OrderService self;
  ...
  self.methodB();  // goes through proxy, @PreAuthorize fires

  CUSTOM SECURITY EXPRESSIONS
  ----------------------------
  Extend DefaultMethodSecurityExpressionHandler to add your own:

  @Component
  public class CustomSecurityExpressionHandler
          extends DefaultMethodSecurityExpressionHandler {

      @Override
      protected MethodSecurityExpressionOperations
              createSecurityExpressionRoot(
                  Authentication auth,
                  MethodInvocation invocation) {
          MySecurityExpressionRoot root =
              new MySecurityExpressionRoot(auth);
          root.setPermissionEvaluator(getPermissionEvaluator());
          root.setTrustResolver(getTrustResolver());
          return root;
      }
  }

  class MySecurityExpressionRoot
          extends SecurityExpressionRoot
          implements MethodSecurityExpressionOperations {

      public boolean isOwnerOf(Long resourceId) {
          Long userId = ((UserDetails)getAuthentication()
                              .getPrincipal()).getId();
          return resourceId.equals(userId);
      }
  }

  // Usage:
  @PreAuthorize("isOwnerOf(#orderId)")
  public Order getOrder(Long orderId) { ... }


